## Who Is Affected

Sunday deserts disproportionately affect three groups most likely to lack car access: elderly residents, low-income households, and young people. For these groups, Sunday service absence is not a minor inconvenience but a genuine barrier to participation in employment (especially in retail, hospitality, and care sectors), NHS appointments, and family connectivity.

The economic cost is measurable: shift-work sectors that rely on Sunday operations — healthcare, hospitality, logistics — cannot recruit effectively from Sunday-desert LSOAs. This contributes to structural unemployment and economic inactivity in the most affected areas.

## Historical Context

Sunday service levels have declined significantly since 2010. The combination of austerity-driven LTA budget cuts and operator commercial withdrawals removed an estimated 30–40% of Sunday services in rural England between 2010 and 2023. The Bus Services Act 2025 and BSIP framework represent the first systematic policy mechanism to reverse this trend.

## Policy Implications

Restoring minimum Sunday service — even 3–4 trips per day — to all currently zero-service LSOAs is costed at approximately £25,000–£50,000 per LSOA per year in contract subsidy. At {{ n_sunday_desert|int|format_thousands }} LSOAs, the national cost of eliminating Sunday deserts entirely would be substantial, but could be phased by targeting the most deprived and populous LSOAs first.

DfT's Bus Service Improvement Plan guidance explicitly identifies Sunday service as a BSIP priority metric. LTAs that demonstrate measurable reduction in Sunday desert LSOAs are prioritised for continued funding.

*Methodology: Sunday service counts from BODS GTFS calendar.txt and trips.txt, aggregated by LSOA spatial join. Sunday desert threshold: zero departures on any Sunday in the analysis period. Weekday baseline uses Monday–Friday average. 1,752,443 total trips processed across 9 BODS GTFS feeds.*
